			Story 2 — Family Left Behind in Aarong Forest

	Bromir often grows quieter when he speaks of this chapter, his voice losing some of the brash pride and replacing it with a gentle, wistful tone.

*"Aarong Forest… I see it in my mind even now, thick green canopies, the scent of pine and the endless rivers glinting in the sunlight. That is where my family still lives, though I have not returned in many, many years. My kin — they were craftsmen, miners, and warriors in their own right. Great dwarves, every one of them, who understood the balance of hammer and anvil, of patience and precision. And I… I left them behind. I chose duty, or perhaps fate chose for me. Sankis called, and the work demanded me, and now, Sunveil holds my hands instead of Aarong."*

	He sighs, running a hand over his beard as though feeling the absence of those distant faces.

*"I worry for them, as a dwarf worries for kin left too long without news. My wife, my two children… I hope they understand why I cannot simply turn back. The island demands my attention, the hunters demand guidance, and the forges will not wait. Yet I tell myself, one day, when my apprentices are truly ready — when they can manage the store, keep the furnaces lit, and maintain the quality of every item forged in my absence — I will return. A short visit, perhaps, to see my family, to smell the pine again, to feel Aarong beneath my boots. Just a brief return, no more than a few days, enough to feel the embrace of the forest and the warmth of hearth that is mine by blood."*

	He shakes his head, a smile creeping onto his face despite the melancholy.

*"Until then, I pour my care into the work here. My apprentices are proxies for my kin, my steel their legacy. If they learn what I have to teach, they will keep my business thriving, and I can journey back knowing all is well. But if they fail… well, then I must remain. Always here, always hammering, teaching, shaping steel, and shaping character. For the sake of those I love, and for the sake of the legacy I cannot abandon."*

	He glances toward the apprentices scurrying around the store, correcting mistakes and wiping soot-streaked faces.

*"Yes… they are my family here now, temporary though it may be. And one day, when they are wise enough to shoulder the work, I will walk Aarong Forest once again, feel the wind through the trees, and hear the laughter of those I left behind. Until then, I forge, I teach, and I wait."*

